WEBVTT

00:03.380 --> 00:04.880
Maggie: Morning, Zola!

00:04.880 --> 00:06.620
Meredith: All diseases have
a genetic component.

00:06.620 --> 00:08.080
Auntie Maggie?
Yes.

00:08.080 --> 00:09.920
Is Grandma Ellis
your mom?

00:09.920 --> 00:11.420
Biologically, yes.

00:11.420 --> 00:15.250
But Diane and Bill raised me,
so they're my mom and dad.

00:15.250 --> 00:16.830
Just like my mom and dad
raised me.

00:16.830 --> 00:18.420
Yup.

00:18.420 --> 00:21.000
But of course, genes are
not always to blame.

00:21.000 --> 00:22.460
Ellis: Margaret, before you
publish your next piece,

00:22.460 --> 00:25.540
you really ought to let me
proofread your work.

00:25.540 --> 00:27.080
It's riddled with typos.

00:27.080 --> 00:28.540
What?

00:28.540 --> 00:31.040
No, it's not!
[ Chuckles ]

00:31.040 --> 00:32.830
And don't make that face.
What face?

00:32.830 --> 00:34.790
That face -- like you've got
some secret we don't know.

00:34.790 --> 00:36.330
The Meredith face.

00:36.330 --> 00:38.580
Well, Meredith got it from me,
so it's the Ellis face.

00:38.580 --> 00:40.080
In diagnosing a disease,

00:40.080 --> 00:43.040
physicians must take into
account other factors.

00:43.040 --> 00:44.420
Who are you?

00:44.420 --> 00:46.420
I'm Derek's sister.
We must have met before.

00:46.420 --> 00:48.210
I think I'd remember.

00:48.210 --> 00:49.330
Would you, though?

00:49.330 --> 00:51.460
Their environment.

00:51.460 --> 00:53.380
Their lifestyle.

00:53.380 --> 00:55.540
♪♪

00:55.540 --> 00:57.120
What does that mean?

00:57.120 --> 00:59.750
Your mom will know.
Quick, write it down.

00:59.750 --> 01:04.000
♪♪

01:04.000 --> 01:06.380
Don't forget to take
your vitamins, dears.

01:06.380 --> 01:08.880
♪♪

01:08.880 --> 01:10.210
[ Gulps ]

01:10.210 --> 01:12.500
[ Mouse squeaking ]

01:12.500 --> 01:13.880
[ Gasps ]

01:13.880 --> 01:15.500
[ Sighs ]

01:17.380 --> 01:21.750
However, some genetic traits
are, annoyingly, unavoidable.

01:21.750 --> 01:27.290
♪♪

01:27.290 --> 01:29.040
Thanks, Mom.

01:29.040 --> 01:30.040
[ Sighs ]

01:37.330 --> 01:39.830
♪ On the move,
out of control ♪

01:39.830 --> 01:42.460
[ Panting ]

01:42.460 --> 01:44.250
♪ Mama said,
"Bless your soul" ♪

01:44.250 --> 01:46.330
[ Cellphone making
"boing" sound ]

01:46.330 --> 01:47.830
♪ Everybody,
move with me now ♪

01:47.830 --> 01:49.040
♪ Wanna see your body
groove with me now ♪

01:49.040 --> 01:50.750
Hey, Mom.

01:50.750 --> 01:52.750
Uh, I'm actually
kind of busy --
Hi, Mrs. Schmitt!

01:52.750 --> 01:55.290
Right. Okay.
[ Laughs ]

01:55.290 --> 01:57.620
Yes, I'll -- I'll --
I'll call you later.

01:57.620 --> 01:59.290
♪ I just wanna get loose,
I just wanna live life ♪

01:59.290 --> 02:01.170
-Ohh.
-Oh. What the hell was that?

02:01.170 --> 02:03.040
Did you just shush me?
No.

02:03.040 --> 02:04.790
♪ I'm feelin', I'm feelin', I'm
feelin', I'm feelin' a vibe ♪

02:04.790 --> 02:06.460
I mean, yes, I did,

02:06.460 --> 02:08.170
but not in
a shame spiral-y way.

02:08.170 --> 02:10.210
Y-Yeah, you just --
You just shushed me.

02:10.210 --> 02:11.250
[ Chuckles ]

02:11.250 --> 02:13.670
It -- It's just she --

02:13.670 --> 02:14.830
[ Clears throat ]

02:14.830 --> 02:17.380
It is not that
I don't want her to know.

02:17.380 --> 02:19.790
She's just...a lot.

02:19.790 --> 02:23.330
She has a lot of opinions
about everything.

02:23.330 --> 02:25.830
Then, what -- you think
she won't like me,

02:25.830 --> 02:27.750
or she won't like
that I'm male?

02:27.750 --> 02:29.330
I just don't want her
to learn about you

02:29.330 --> 02:31.710
as the hot shirtless guy
I'm in bed with.

02:31.710 --> 02:33.000
♪ Let it loose,
just let it go ♪

02:33.000 --> 02:35.540
Even though you are hot

02:35.540 --> 02:38.670
and shirtless
and in bed with me.

02:38.670 --> 02:40.790
Not anymore.

02:40.790 --> 02:43.120
♪ Wanna see your body groove
with me now ♪

02:43.120 --> 02:44.830
♪ Wanna see how
you lay it down ♪
[ Sighs lightly ]

02:44.830 --> 02:46.670
♪ Lay it down ♪

02:46.670 --> 02:47.790
♪ Day and night ♪

02:47.790 --> 02:48.960
♪♪

02:48.960 --> 02:50.830
DeLuca: Hey, you.

02:50.830 --> 02:53.080
Helm says you, uh, handed off
all your surgeries.

02:53.080 --> 02:54.750
What are you working on?

02:54.750 --> 02:56.170
I'm not totally sure yet.

02:56.170 --> 02:57.790
It -- It came to me
in a dream.

02:57.790 --> 02:59.540
You dream science?

02:59.540 --> 03:02.620
Rarely, but thank you.

03:02.620 --> 03:03.830
How's it going
with your dad?

03:03.830 --> 03:05.250
Weirdly, not terrible.

03:05.250 --> 03:06.920
He seems stable,
but it's hard to tell.

03:06.920 --> 03:08.960
He's here today
with a pitch.
A pitch?

03:08.960 --> 03:10.830
A medical breakthrough,
he says.

03:10.830 --> 03:12.710
[ Imitating Nico ] "It's gonna
change the world, Andrea."

03:12.710 --> 03:14.040
[ Both laugh ]

03:14.040 --> 03:15.880
He gets these big ideas,
he gets obsessed with them,

03:15.880 --> 03:18.330
and then he just cycles out
and loses interest.

03:18.330 --> 03:20.330
It -- It probably won't
amount to much.

03:20.330 --> 03:22.580
Is there
a diagnosis or...?
No.

03:22.580 --> 03:24.620
But Carina seems to think
he's got bipolar,

03:24.620 --> 03:26.080
but he refuses treatment,
of course,

03:26.080 --> 03:28.120
so we don't really know.

03:28.120 --> 03:31.040
He just says he, uh,
feels the world deeply.

03:31.040 --> 03:32.290
Well, that's poetic.

03:32.290 --> 03:34.420
Oh, he has his charms.
[ Laughs ]

03:34.420 --> 03:35.750
♪ Whoah, oh, oh, oh, oh,
put up your hands ♪

03:35.750 --> 03:37.960
[ Cellphone rings ]

03:37.960 --> 03:39.880
♪ Just dance ♪

03:39.880 --> 03:41.000
I got to go.

03:41.000 --> 03:42.170
Keep me posted.

03:42.170 --> 03:43.460
Okay.

03:43.460 --> 03:44.710
♪ Put up your hands ♪

03:44.710 --> 03:46.790
-We have rules.
-Okay.

03:46.790 --> 03:48.170
♪ Just dance ♪

03:48.170 --> 03:50.460
♪ Oh, oh, oh, oh, oh ♪

03:50.460 --> 03:52.580
♪ Oh, oh, oh, oh, oh ♪

03:52.580 --> 03:53.710
♪ Whoah, oh, oh, oh, oh ♪

03:53.710 --> 03:54.750
[ Breathes deeply ]

03:54.750 --> 03:55.960
♪ Hey! ♪

03:55.960 --> 03:57.880
[ Telephone rings in distance ]

03:57.880 --> 03:59.420
Hey.
Hello.

03:59.420 --> 04:02.620
More interviews?
Yeah, some medical podcast.

04:02.620 --> 04:04.120
[ Scoffs ]
She's on fire, though.

04:04.120 --> 04:06.500
Why do they call it that?

04:06.500 --> 04:08.120
"Podcast."

04:08.120 --> 04:09.460
I mean,
there's pea pods.

04:09.460 --> 04:11.830
There are certain pods
in aviation.

04:11.830 --> 04:13.210
Whales swim in pods,

04:13.210 --> 04:16.000
but that word has nothing to do
with audio recording.

04:16.000 --> 04:19.040
Right. Uh, I got
a rotation-plasty.

04:19.040 --> 04:20.040
What does that
have to do with --

04:20.040 --> 04:21.710
[ Clears throat ]
Nothing, sir.

04:21.710 --> 04:23.420
[ Telephone rings in distance ]

04:23.420 --> 04:25.080
[ Indistinct conversations ]

04:25.080 --> 04:27.170
Podcaster: We hear
you were a bit of a prodigy.

04:27.170 --> 04:29.250
You finished
med school at 19.

04:29.250 --> 04:32.330
You made chief of cardio
at Tufts at 27.

04:32.330 --> 04:33.330
Impressive.
Yeah.

04:33.330 --> 04:35.000
Thank you. Yes.

04:35.000 --> 04:36.750
Um, I had
a very strong family.

04:36.750 --> 04:39.000
My parents told me I could be
whatever I wanted to be.

04:39.000 --> 04:40.380
Are they surgeons,
as well?

04:40.380 --> 04:42.000
Oh, God, no.
[ Laughs ]

04:42.000 --> 04:44.210
Then what drew you
to the field?

04:44.210 --> 04:45.540
You know,
I can't really remember

04:45.540 --> 04:47.670
ever not wanting
to be a doctor.

04:47.670 --> 04:50.170
I knew at age 12 that
I wanted to be a surgeon.

04:50.170 --> 04:51.620
By 14,
that it was cardio.

04:51.620 --> 04:53.290
-Wow. Born to be a surgeon.
-[ Chuckles ]

04:53.290 --> 04:55.790
Yeah, yeah. It makes you wonder
about a genetic component.

04:55.790 --> 04:57.460
Uh, genetic?

04:57.460 --> 05:00.710
Yeah. Well, both my biological
parents were surgeons.

05:00.710 --> 05:03.790
Although Ellis and Richard
were both in general surgery.

05:03.790 --> 05:05.290
Same with my sister,
Meredith.

05:05.290 --> 05:07.040
So I don't know where
the hearts come in.

05:07.040 --> 05:08.790
That must be
nurture over nature.

05:08.790 --> 05:11.330
I'm -- I'm sorry. Did you say
Ellis and Meredith?

05:11.330 --> 05:12.790
-Hm?
-As in Grey?

05:12.790 --> 05:14.540
Ellis and Meredith Grey?

05:14.540 --> 05:17.080
Oh.

05:17.080 --> 05:18.830
Well, ah --
M-My point was that --

05:18.830 --> 05:21.120
And -- And Richard is...?

05:21.120 --> 05:24.540
Uh, my -- my biological father,
Richard Webber.

05:24.540 --> 05:26.460
I'm sorry.
Are you saying that Ellis Grey,

05:26.460 --> 05:28.500
two-time Harper Avery Award
winner,

05:28.500 --> 05:31.290
mother of Meredith Grey,
is your birth mother?

05:31.290 --> 05:33.540
Um...

05:33.540 --> 05:35.710
M-M-Maybe
we can edit that.

05:35.710 --> 05:37.040
-Holy crap.
-Wow.

05:37.040 --> 05:38.420
[ Breathes sharply ]

05:38.420 --> 05:40.040
♪♪

05:40.040 --> 05:42.330
Alex: I mean, it's not exactly
a real library, but it's...

05:42.330 --> 05:44.420
Would it be okay if I did
a little sorting?

05:44.420 --> 05:46.620
Seems like doctors
don't put books back

05:46.620 --> 05:47.460
where they found them.

05:47.460 --> 05:48.880
Oh, sure.

05:48.880 --> 05:50.330
Sorry, but I have
back-to-back meetings.

05:50.330 --> 05:51.750
I'll come back
and grab you for lunch.

05:51.750 --> 05:53.210
Okay?

05:53.210 --> 05:54.790
My son, the chief.

05:54.790 --> 05:56.790
Oh, my God.
This is so cute!

05:56.790 --> 05:59.250
Thank you. Those are
for my grandchildren.

05:59.250 --> 06:00.920
Oh! Is Amber having
another baby?

06:00.920 --> 06:02.710
No.
Those are for yours.

06:04.120 --> 06:06.830
Our -- Our what?
Kids.

06:06.830 --> 06:09.290
Uh, you know, I was reading
an article about how gender

06:09.290 --> 06:12.620
is a more fluid concept than
previous generations realized.

06:12.620 --> 06:15.880
So I figured
that purple, green...

06:15.880 --> 06:17.620
Neutral colors.

06:17.620 --> 06:19.290
Mm-hmm.

06:19.290 --> 06:20.540
Hm.

06:21.960 --> 06:23.460
We're in
the baby hat place?

06:23.460 --> 06:24.920
Are you pregnant
and you didn't tell me?

06:24.920 --> 06:28.460
She asked me if we wanted kids,
and I said yes because we do.

06:28.460 --> 06:30.120
And she's making the hats
extra big

06:30.120 --> 06:31.580
because I had
an extra big head.

06:31.580 --> 06:32.790
Which, now that
I say it out loud,

06:32.790 --> 06:34.790
probably sounds daunting.

06:34.790 --> 06:35.880
I have a surgery.
[ Elevator bell dings ]

06:35.880 --> 06:37.960
What surgery?

06:37.960 --> 06:39.250
Hey -- Hey, Bailey.

06:39.250 --> 06:40.170
Woman on P.A.:
Dr. Hobb to...

06:40.170 --> 06:41.710
Dr. Hobb...

06:41.710 --> 06:43.540
Hunt and Altman are both
taking personal days,

06:43.540 --> 06:45.000
so I need you
to cover the pit today.

06:46.330 --> 06:47.790
Please?

06:47.790 --> 06:49.120
How many?
How many what?

06:49.120 --> 06:50.920
Days left.
Till what?

06:50.920 --> 06:52.540
Till I stop taking orders
from you.

06:52.540 --> 06:53.960
22.

06:53.960 --> 06:55.460
Mm-hmm.

06:55.460 --> 06:56.420
Woman on P.A.:
Dr. Oliver to Radiology.

06:56.420 --> 06:58.670
Dr. Danny Oliver
to Radiology.

06:58.670 --> 07:00.580
-Maybe.
-Kidding.

07:00.580 --> 07:02.620
-Hey, Link!
-Hey, number 20.

07:02.620 --> 07:04.170
[ Laughs ]

07:04.170 --> 07:06.460
-Yeah. Heh!
-[ Laughs ]

07:06.460 --> 07:08.380
All right.
Jackson Avery, plastics.

07:08.380 --> 07:09.460
Jenny Martinez, mother.

07:09.460 --> 07:11.040
-Nice to meet you.
-You I know.

07:11.040 --> 07:14.170
Come here with that face.
[ Laughs ]

07:14.170 --> 07:15.830
We miss you
at the clubhouse.

07:15.830 --> 07:17.040
You're gonna get him
squared away

07:17.040 --> 07:18.620
so he can get called up
next year, right?

07:18.620 --> 07:20.170
That is the hope.

07:20.170 --> 07:22.000
But it's gonna be
a long road.

07:22.000 --> 07:23.710
Dr. Kim, all you.

07:23.710 --> 07:26.000
Kim: Okay. Hunter Martinez,
20 years old,

07:26.000 --> 07:28.420
diagnosed with osteosarcoma
of the distal right femur,

07:28.420 --> 07:30.040
here for
a rotation-plasty.

07:30.040 --> 07:31.540
Uh, what exactly
is that?

07:31.540 --> 07:33.290
He only told me about this
last week,

07:33.290 --> 07:34.620
so I'm playing catch-up.

07:34.620 --> 07:37.080
She worries too much.
Show her the cartoon.

07:37.080 --> 07:39.580
Okay.
[ Clicks ]

07:39.580 --> 07:43.000
We will begin by removing
the lower end of the femur,

07:43.000 --> 07:44.960
the knee joint,
and the upper tibia.

07:44.960 --> 07:48.250
Then rotate the lower leg
180 degrees

07:48.250 --> 07:50.710
and re-attach
the remainder of the leg.

07:50.710 --> 07:52.380
The ankle joint will serve
as the new knee joint

07:52.380 --> 07:53.790
to fit in
for the prosthetic leg.

07:53.790 --> 07:55.080
Oh, my God!

07:55.080 --> 07:56.250
Now, don't worry,
Jenny.

07:56.250 --> 07:57.960
He's already done
his three months of chemo,

07:57.960 --> 08:00.170
so this surgery will leave him
cancer-free --
Three months?

08:02.500 --> 08:04.170
You've known about this
for three months?

08:04.170 --> 08:05.290
I didn't want
to freak you out.

08:05.290 --> 08:07.170
Freak me out?!

08:07.170 --> 08:08.880
[ Telephone rings in distance ]

08:11.710 --> 08:14.290
We'll, uh...

08:14.290 --> 08:16.960
talk about this later.

08:16.960 --> 08:20.330
Please, um...
continue.

08:20.330 --> 08:21.880
Nico: Okay. Well,
the first step would be

08:21.880 --> 08:23.460
to make an incision
in the thigh.

08:23.460 --> 08:24.920
Woman on P.A.:
Dr. Swan to Oncology.

08:24.920 --> 08:26.460
Nice to meet you,
Mr. DeLuca.

08:26.460 --> 08:27.620
Or should I say
"Doctor"?

08:27.620 --> 08:29.210
It is, grazie.
[ Door closes ]

08:29.210 --> 08:31.420
Uh, bambini,
you can go now.

08:31.420 --> 08:33.210
I can help
with the English.

08:33.210 --> 08:35.290
[ Laughs ] You?

08:35.290 --> 08:37.380
You can barely speak it
yourself.

08:37.380 --> 08:39.290
I can help.
And, plus, I'm curious to see

08:39.290 --> 08:42.000
what this research is
you're presenting today.

08:42.000 --> 08:43.000
Okay.

08:48.790 --> 08:50.580
[ Laptop thuds gently ]

08:53.790 --> 08:56.790
It is a baby in a bag.

08:56.790 --> 08:58.040
Okay.

08:58.040 --> 08:59.880
1 in 10 babies
is born preterm

08:59.880 --> 09:02.420
because mother
can't carry child to term

09:02.420 --> 09:04.880
due to trauma or accident,
so many reasons.

09:04.880 --> 09:06.670
And the baby, she dies.

09:06.670 --> 09:09.830
Premature babies cannot survive
outside the mama.

09:09.830 --> 09:12.960
But what if it could?

09:12.960 --> 09:15.750
What if we transferred the baby
from the mama

09:15.750 --> 09:18.420
to an external
gestational sac

09:18.420 --> 09:22.250
so her little lungs
and her brain and her heart,

09:22.250 --> 09:24.420
they can develop?

09:24.420 --> 09:27.920
And then we give her
the birth, yes?

09:27.920 --> 09:29.620
From the bag,

09:29.620 --> 09:34.880
a beautiful, full-term,
healthy baby!

09:34.880 --> 09:37.790
You want to create
an external gestational sac?

09:37.790 --> 09:40.000
No.
I have already.

09:40.000 --> 09:43.210
♪♪

09:43.210 --> 09:46.580
I am in animal trials.

09:46.580 --> 09:48.750
Four ovine
subject subjects.

09:48.750 --> 09:51.880
The latest showed normal pH
and lactate levels,

09:51.880 --> 09:53.670
good fetal circulation,

09:53.670 --> 09:54.830
and then...

09:54.830 --> 09:56.170
Eccolo!

09:56.170 --> 10:00.250
Born at 125 days.

10:00.250 --> 10:03.210
That lamb gestated?
In a bag.

10:03.210 --> 10:06.000
It's a baby in a bag.

10:06.000 --> 10:06.830
[ Lamb bleating ]

10:06.830 --> 10:08.880
You'll fund this, yes?

10:08.880 --> 10:12.500
♪♪

10:19.620 --> 10:22.960
Britney's signature,
her parents' signature...

10:22.960 --> 10:24.920
Everything's notarized.
[ Breathes deeply ]

10:24.920 --> 10:27.750
Well, I have good news
and bad news.

10:27.750 --> 10:28.880
Is something wrong?

10:28.880 --> 10:30.580
No. That's the good news
and the bad news.

10:30.580 --> 10:31.960
This is so straightforward,

10:31.960 --> 10:33.290
I'm not gonna be able
to bill you for many hours.

10:33.290 --> 10:35.250
-Oh.
-[ Laughs ]

10:35.250 --> 10:37.040
So, let's get started
with you two.

10:37.040 --> 10:38.500
Uh, what is Leo's address?

10:40.080 --> 10:41.920
[ Telephone rings in distance ]

10:41.920 --> 10:43.830
Uh, trick question.

10:43.830 --> 10:45.210
It's really your address.

10:45.210 --> 10:46.290
[ Scoffs ]
No, it's -- it's not that.

10:46.290 --> 10:47.960
Just we don't live
together.

10:47.960 --> 10:49.120
-We used to...
-Yeah.

10:49.120 --> 10:51.290
-...uh, but not anymore.
-Mnh-mnh.

10:51.290 --> 10:52.750
Oh. [ Exhales slowly ]

10:52.750 --> 10:55.460
-Is that a problem?
-Well, you tell me.

10:55.460 --> 10:57.120
Because if the two of you are
gonna be fighting for custody,

10:57.120 --> 10:58.120
I mean, that's --
No, no, no, no.

10:58.120 --> 10:59.500
Neither of --
of us wants that.

10:59.500 --> 11:00.920
We are totally committed
to Leo...
Yeah.

11:00.920 --> 11:03.920
...and, um, we want
what's best for him.

11:03.920 --> 11:05.620
Then we should be good.

11:05.620 --> 11:07.000
But I am gonna have to
take back what I said

11:07.000 --> 11:08.960
about this
not being complicated.

11:08.960 --> 11:11.040
[ Telephone rings in distance ]

11:11.040 --> 11:12.080
[ Horn honks in distance,
indistinct conversations ]

11:12.080 --> 11:13.420
Wait, wait, wait!
I, uh --

11:13.420 --> 11:14.920
I need you to put me
on a surgery.

11:14.920 --> 11:16.380
-Any surgery.
-Why?

11:16.380 --> 11:18.290
Because I told my husband
I had a surgery.

11:18.290 --> 11:20.210
Got it.
What are you avoiding?

11:20.210 --> 11:23.170
Telling you would defeat
the purpose of avoiding it.

11:23.170 --> 11:24.920
Oh, God.
Oh, what's happening? No.

11:24.920 --> 11:27.170
Eye contact.
Oh.

11:27.170 --> 11:29.210
God, I am so embarrassed
for you both.

11:29.210 --> 11:30.960
We're doing
a rotation-plasty, so...

11:30.960 --> 11:32.540
You're turning an ankle
into a knee?

11:32.540 --> 11:33.920
-I want in.
-Okay.

11:33.920 --> 11:35.170
Schmitt, you're out.

11:35.170 --> 11:37.040
I've been studying for this
surgery for three weeks.

11:37.040 --> 11:38.670
Seniority.
Special treatment.

11:38.670 --> 11:40.670
Oh, yeah?
How'd you get in on it?

11:40.670 --> 11:43.250
Jackson: Oh.

11:43.250 --> 11:44.790
Sorry, bud.
Too many cooks.

11:44.790 --> 11:46.710
Karev, prep the patient.

11:46.710 --> 11:49.460
Oh, and, uh, tell his mom
where to hang.

11:49.460 --> 11:51.170
She's a little freaked.
Okay.

11:52.830 --> 11:54.460
[ Door opens ]

11:54.460 --> 11:56.540
Ooh, whatcha working on?

11:56.540 --> 11:58.960
Well, Ellis came to me
last night in a dream

11:58.960 --> 12:00.290
and gave me
the answer to something.

12:00.290 --> 12:01.880
I just don't know
what the question is.

12:01.880 --> 12:03.290
Huh.

12:03.290 --> 12:04.960
Ellis got into my head
this morning, too.

12:04.960 --> 12:06.210
Did she give you
the question?

12:06.210 --> 12:07.460
No, I was doing
that podcast,

12:07.460 --> 12:08.750
you know,
for my article...
Uh-huh.

12:08.750 --> 12:10.290
...and I accidentally
let it slip

12:10.290 --> 12:11.460
to the entire
medical community

12:11.460 --> 12:13.330
that I'm her secret
love child.

12:15.960 --> 12:18.380
Oh.

12:18.380 --> 12:20.210
Well, that's not
that big a deal.

12:20.210 --> 12:22.380
You said, "Oh,"
and you made a face.

12:22.380 --> 12:23.790
Maggie, that's your life.

12:23.790 --> 12:24.790
Well, yeah.

12:24.790 --> 12:26.540
And -- And yours.
And Richard's.

12:26.540 --> 12:29.210
[ Sighs ]

12:29.210 --> 12:31.330
Biomarkers?
What?

12:31.330 --> 12:33.170
Ellis. The question.
Was it about biomarkers?

12:34.080 --> 12:35.920
You're a genius.

12:35.920 --> 12:37.290
Yeah, it's in our DNA.

12:37.290 --> 12:39.210
[ Marker squeaking ]

12:39.210 --> 12:40.960
Ugh.
Maggie,
Richard will be fine.

12:40.960 --> 12:42.290
He's Richard.

12:44.380 --> 12:45.380
Okay.

12:46.830 --> 12:48.540
[ Wheels squeaking ]

12:48.540 --> 12:50.710
[ Door opens ]

12:50.710 --> 12:52.670
[ Telephone rings in distance,
indistinct conversations ]

12:52.670 --> 12:54.710
Woman on P.A.:
Rhys Joseph to Peds ICU.

12:54.710 --> 12:57.120
Rhys Joseph to Peds ICU.

12:57.120 --> 12:59.170
[ Indistinct conversations ]

12:59.170 --> 13:01.750
[ Door creaks ]

13:01.750 --> 13:03.960
[ Telephone rings in distance ]

13:03.960 --> 13:05.250
How long will that take?

13:05.250 --> 13:06.380
It could be
around eight hours,

13:06.380 --> 13:07.790
but we'll make sure
to update you.

13:07.790 --> 13:08.880
And what time
will that be?

13:08.880 --> 13:10.210
Every couple of hours.

13:12.330 --> 13:14.120
It's normal
to be scared.

13:15.750 --> 13:18.170
I'm not scared.
I'm enraged.

13:18.170 --> 13:19.620
This child, who I poured

13:19.620 --> 13:21.750
my blood and sweat
and soul into --

13:21.750 --> 13:24.170
my child didn't tell me
about three months of chemo

13:24.170 --> 13:25.880
'cause he didn't
want me to freak,

13:25.880 --> 13:28.120
so now I-I-I'm not allowed
to freak or I prove him right,

13:28.120 --> 13:29.540
and I'm not allowed to rage

13:29.540 --> 13:31.580
because you're turning
his ankle into his knee,

13:31.580 --> 13:33.040
so I have to
be supportive!

13:33.040 --> 13:34.830
[ Telephone rings in distance ]

13:34.830 --> 13:36.210
[ Exhales deeply ]

13:38.120 --> 13:41.170
Is there a gym
in this hospital

13:41.170 --> 13:42.920
with some kind of
punching bag?

13:42.920 --> 13:43.790
[ Siren wailing in distance ]

13:43.790 --> 13:45.710
I'm sorry, Dr. Bailey.

13:45.710 --> 13:47.750
I was on the OR floor,
so it took me a minute.
Stop, Schmitt.

13:47.750 --> 13:49.250
I'm bored already.

13:49.250 --> 13:51.500
Bed 3.
Frank Nelstadt, 47.

13:51.500 --> 13:54.750
Chief complaint -- fever,
sore throat, productive cough.

13:54.750 --> 13:57.790
O2 sat 88% on room air.

13:57.790 --> 13:59.170
Enjoy.

13:59.170 --> 14:01.250
-It's Dad.
-I'm kinda busy, Ella.

14:01.250 --> 14:02.500
Mr. Nelstadt,
I'm Dr. Schmitt.

14:02.500 --> 14:03.620
How long have you had
that cough?

14:03.620 --> 14:05.540
Uh, I don't know.
A few days?

14:05.540 --> 14:07.620
It's not as bad
as it seems.

14:07.620 --> 14:09.000
Don't think
I didn't see you

14:09.000 --> 14:10.290
just decline my call,
honey.

14:10.290 --> 14:12.420
You're supposed to be
at a conference.

14:12.420 --> 14:14.880
[ Sighs ] I was, until
our daughter ratted you out.

14:14.880 --> 14:17.210
[ Chuckles, coughing ]
"Dad hacking up lung.

14:17.210 --> 14:19.830
Sounds like dying moose.
So gross."

14:19.830 --> 14:22.420
We've raised such a sensitive
and supportive young woman.

14:22.420 --> 14:23.670
[ Scoffs ]

14:23.670 --> 14:25.420
Sir, do you have
any chest pain?

14:25.420 --> 14:27.080
I'd like to get an X-ray,
maybe a CT,

14:27.080 --> 14:28.670
just to rule out
anything more serious.

14:28.670 --> 14:30.380
A CT? Really?
Dan.

14:30.380 --> 14:32.170
How old are you?
Danny!

14:32.170 --> 14:34.500
Sorry, Doctor, my husband
spins out over a hangnail.

14:34.500 --> 14:37.210
Dan--
Excuse me. Hi.
Are you in charge here?

14:37.210 --> 14:39.540
Because, uh, there's a child
doctor working on my husband,

14:39.540 --> 14:41.460
and I would like for you
to change that.

14:41.460 --> 14:43.040
Uh, Dr. Schmitt
is a surgical resident.
Levi: All right,
deep breath in.

14:43.040 --> 14:44.250
Mm-hmm.
And although
he looks young, he does --

14:44.250 --> 14:45.290
All right, I-I'm sorry.

14:45.290 --> 14:46.420
It's not in my nature
to be rude,

14:46.420 --> 14:48.290
so I-I'm hoping
you're gonna forgive me

14:48.290 --> 14:50.380
and know that this is just
the fear talking when I say...
[ Frank coughing ]

14:50.380 --> 14:52.750
...if my husband needs a CT,
then I need for him

14:52.750 --> 14:54.830
to have
a grown-ass doctor.

14:54.830 --> 14:56.460
[ Monitor beeps rapidly ]

14:56.460 --> 14:58.000
Sir, lean forward.

14:58.000 --> 15:00.330
Frank? Frank!
Can he breathe?

15:00.330 --> 15:02.120
Let's prepare for
a possible RSI

15:02.120 --> 15:04.120
with 100 sux,
100 propofol,

15:04.120 --> 15:06.750
and get
an intubation tray ready.

15:06.750 --> 15:08.920
[ Coughs ]

15:08.920 --> 15:10.790
-Oh, my God!
-Ohh.

15:10.790 --> 15:12.540
I do not enjoy this.

15:12.540 --> 15:14.250
Okay.

15:14.250 --> 15:15.540
[ Breathes sharply ]

15:15.540 --> 15:17.880
♪♪

15:17.880 --> 15:19.290
Oh, that feels better.

15:24.750 --> 15:26.670
[ Saw whirring ]
♪ I-I-I can feel it ♪

15:26.670 --> 15:28.000
♪ I can feel it ♪

15:28.000 --> 15:30.670
♪ I can feel it ♪

15:30.670 --> 15:34.170
All right.
Upper dissection complete.

15:34.170 --> 15:35.540
Let's go ahead
and remove the specimen.

15:35.540 --> 15:36.790
We're ready
from the lower end.

15:36.790 --> 15:38.080
Jo, the honors?

15:38.080 --> 15:40.670
Yes, please. Ohh.

15:40.670 --> 15:43.710
I can't believe Hunter didn't
tell his mom he had a tumor.

15:43.710 --> 15:46.250
Oh, he told her.
Just not till last week.

15:46.250 --> 15:47.460
Ah, he was trying
to protect her.

15:47.460 --> 15:49.210
Stupid, but I understand
the impulse.

15:49.210 --> 15:50.040
All right.
Let's rotate the leg.

15:50.040 --> 15:51.790
-[ Clears throat ]
-Okay.

15:51.790 --> 15:54.500
Can you get the tibial plates
and screws ready, please?

15:54.500 --> 15:56.120
Speaking of parents,

15:56.120 --> 15:57.830
how's it going with
the mother-in-law?

15:57.830 --> 15:59.620
Still here.
Still sleeping on our couch.

15:59.620 --> 16:01.670
Oof. In a loft?
That sounds cozy.

16:01.670 --> 16:03.330
No, it's fine.

16:03.330 --> 16:05.670
She's sweet, and she doesn't
take up a lot of space,

16:05.670 --> 16:08.000
and she just makes tea all day,
and she knits.

16:08.000 --> 16:09.380
So that's what
you're avoiding.

16:09.380 --> 16:11.380
No.
Who's avoiding?

16:11.380 --> 16:12.790
Jo wanted to scrub in
for a distraction.

16:12.790 --> 16:14.670
[ Sighs ] It's not Helen.
Helen is fine.

16:14.670 --> 16:16.540
I'm happy that she's here
and that she's doing well

16:16.540 --> 16:17.790
and that she is
knitting hats.

16:17.790 --> 16:19.290
A lot of them.
For babies.

16:19.290 --> 16:21.330
For our babies, apparently,
that her and Alex are planning

16:21.330 --> 16:22.920
just full steam ahead --

16:22.920 --> 16:26.420
gender neutral, big-headed
baby hats and all.

16:26.420 --> 16:27.540
[ Sighs ] Lap pad.

16:27.540 --> 16:29.210
♪ Ooh-ooh, ooh-ooh-ooh-ooh,
ooh-ooh ♪

16:29.210 --> 16:31.330
I think we got
what she's avoiding.
[ Sighs ]

16:31.330 --> 16:35.120
♪ Ooh-ooh, ooh-ooh-ooh-ooh,
ooh-ooh ♪

16:35.120 --> 16:37.500
♪ Ooh-ooh, ooh-ooh-ooh-ooh,
ooh-ooh ♪
[ Sighs ]

16:37.500 --> 16:39.960
-You paged me to the lab?
-I did.

16:39.960 --> 16:41.620
[ Chair wheels squeak ]

16:41.620 --> 16:43.420
What -- you couldn't come
to my office?

16:43.420 --> 16:45.540
I couldn't.
[ Sighs ]

16:45.540 --> 16:46.460
Why not?

16:46.460 --> 16:47.710
Because that would be
a concession

16:47.710 --> 16:49.790
to your superior job title,
and that's about to end.

16:49.790 --> 16:51.210
But it hasn't ended.

16:51.210 --> 16:52.790
No, but when it does,
I just don't want the fall

16:52.790 --> 16:54.500
to hurt too badly.

16:54.500 --> 16:56.250
What are you working on?

16:56.250 --> 16:58.080
My mother gave me
a tip.

16:58.080 --> 16:59.670
About what?
Never mind.

16:59.670 --> 17:01.250
How'd it go
with Vincenzo DeLuca?

17:01.250 --> 17:02.750
Oh, his pitch
was awesome.

17:02.750 --> 17:05.620
It's a freaking
baby in a bag.

17:05.620 --> 17:06.710
A baby in a bag?

17:06.710 --> 17:07.750
Yeah, an external womb.

17:07.750 --> 17:08.920
He's already made
a prototype.

17:08.920 --> 17:11.880
He showed us the video
of the baby lamb.

17:11.880 --> 17:13.290
In a bag?
Yup.

17:13.290 --> 17:14.710
10 years in peds,
and I have never thought

17:14.710 --> 17:16.290
of something so cool.

17:16.290 --> 17:18.120
Almost sounds too good
to be true.
[ Crunching ]

17:18.120 --> 17:19.920
Yeah, well, I asked him
to give me a day or two,

17:19.920 --> 17:22.790
but I wanted to say yes
in that room.

17:22.790 --> 17:24.790
Did you call his hospital
in Italy?

17:24.790 --> 17:27.290
Yeah. They love him.

17:27.290 --> 17:29.040
[ Crunching ]

17:29.040 --> 17:30.040
You should dig
a little deeper --

17:30.040 --> 17:31.830
kick the tires
on that one.

17:31.830 --> 17:32.670
Why?
What do you know?

17:34.540 --> 17:35.750
What?

17:35.750 --> 17:36.670
Read my face.

17:38.210 --> 17:39.830
Constipated?

17:39.830 --> 17:42.960
My face is saying something
that I cannot say.

17:42.960 --> 17:44.500
Oh, this is about Jo.

17:44.500 --> 17:45.500
Did she talk to you
about my mom

17:45.500 --> 17:46.540
[Chuckling]
and the baby hats?

17:46.540 --> 17:47.880
[ Chuckling ] Oh.

17:47.880 --> 17:50.120
[ Inhales sharply ]
Never mind.

17:50.120 --> 17:51.080
Fine.

17:51.080 --> 17:53.170
[ Crunches loudly ]

17:54.830 --> 17:56.420
So, are you planning on
alternating weeks

17:56.420 --> 17:57.670
or splitting weeks?

17:57.670 --> 17:58.670
2-2-3?

17:58.670 --> 17:59.960
2-2-3 is...?

17:59.960 --> 18:01.620
You each get two days,

18:01.620 --> 18:03.330
and then whoever went first
gets three,

18:03.330 --> 18:04.500
and then, the next week,
you flip it

18:04.500 --> 18:05.580
so the time balances out.

18:05.580 --> 18:07.460
Um...

18:07.460 --> 18:10.170
W-We haven't had much time
to discuss it, so...

18:10.170 --> 18:12.380
The judge is gonna
want to know.

18:12.380 --> 18:14.540
Well, I don't want to spend
half my time away from him.

18:14.540 --> 18:16.540
She gave custody
to both of us.

18:16.540 --> 18:18.290
Yeah, but she didn't know
that you'd just left me.

18:18.290 --> 18:19.920
Maybe she would've made
a different decision.

18:19.920 --> 18:21.710
Okay, so you don't even
want me on the paperwork.

18:21.710 --> 18:23.040
No, no.
That's not what I'm saying.

18:23.040 --> 18:25.120
I'm just saying there's
an argument to be made

18:25.120 --> 18:26.960
in favor of consistency.

18:26.960 --> 18:29.290
Okay, folks, uh,
we're done here.

18:29.290 --> 18:31.080
Uh, no, wait.
We will --
Uh.

18:31.080 --> 18:32.540
-We're gonna figure it out.
-"We'll figure it out"

18:32.540 --> 18:34.210
isn't the kind of answer
I can give a judge.

18:34.210 --> 18:36.000
Listen, this went longer
than expected

18:36.000 --> 18:38.620
and I have another meeting,
but use the room.

18:38.620 --> 18:39.960
If you want this child
in your life,

18:39.960 --> 18:43.000
you're gonna need
to get on the same page, fast.

18:44.500 --> 18:46.120
[ Footsteps departing ]

18:46.120 --> 18:49.040
[ Door opens, closes ]

18:49.040 --> 18:50.540
[ Coughing ]

18:50.540 --> 18:52.380
Danny: She said,
"Dad's coughing up a lung,"

18:52.380 --> 18:53.920
and now he just
coughed up a lung.

18:53.920 --> 18:56.120
It's not his lung,
or he would be dead.

18:56.120 --> 18:58.210
Uh, according
to image search,

18:58.210 --> 19:00.120
it's a --
a bronchial tree.

19:00.120 --> 19:01.960
Uh, it's actually
a blood clot

19:01.960 --> 19:03.750
in the shape
of a bronchial tree.

19:03.750 --> 19:05.290
Somehow, the coughing

19:05.290 --> 19:07.290
must've cause bleeding
in his airway,

19:07.290 --> 19:09.500
but how it became
so congealed and --

19:09.500 --> 19:11.170
[ Breathing quickly ]

19:11.170 --> 19:12.290
-What's happening?
-Dad?

19:12.290 --> 19:13.830
[ Monitor beeps rapidly ]
Are you okay?

19:13.830 --> 19:16.290
Okay. Schmitt, intubate
while I do an ultrasound.

19:16.290 --> 19:18.080
Um, I'm sorry.
Move back, please.

19:18.080 --> 19:19.710
Let's get a crash cart
in here

19:19.710 --> 19:21.620
and the sux and propofol
that I asked for

19:21.620 --> 19:22.880
and an EKG.

19:22.880 --> 19:24.500
What happened?
He was just fine!

19:24.500 --> 19:25.580
Dad, come on.
Let them work.

19:25.580 --> 19:26.830
Come on,
let's move, Schmitt.

19:26.830 --> 19:28.210
[ Rapid beeping continues ]

19:28.210 --> 19:31.380
This could be a massive
pulmonary embolus.

19:31.380 --> 19:33.330
You ever hear an idea
that's so good

19:33.330 --> 19:35.620
that it makes you angry
you didn't think of it?

19:35.620 --> 19:37.380
Yes.

19:37.380 --> 19:40.000
But it usually means
my meds aren't working.

19:40.000 --> 19:42.500
I spent several years
in an outright rage

19:42.500 --> 19:43.580
that I didn't invent

19:43.580 --> 19:44.710
[Chuckling]
the cordless phone.

19:46.750 --> 19:48.830
When I was little, what did
you think I was gonna be

19:48.830 --> 19:50.790
when I grew up?

19:50.790 --> 19:53.120
Well, you once asked me

19:53.120 --> 19:55.580
what the inside of a doorknob
looked like.

19:55.580 --> 19:57.080
I mean, you were 6,

19:57.080 --> 19:58.580
so I just took it apart
and showed it to you.

19:58.580 --> 20:02.170
But then you wouldn't let me
put it back together again.

20:02.170 --> 20:03.580
Eventually,
you did it yourself,

20:03.580 --> 20:07.040
so I thought you were
gonna be an engineer.

20:07.040 --> 20:08.290
Oh, yeah, well,
taking things apart

20:08.290 --> 20:09.830
and putting them
back together again

20:09.830 --> 20:11.960
is kind of
what I do all day.

20:11.960 --> 20:13.620
[ Chuckling ]
That's true.

20:13.620 --> 20:15.000
But I'm not really
a thinker.

20:16.620 --> 20:19.420
I mean, I'm a fixer,
not an innovator.

20:21.080 --> 20:23.290
Oh, I don't know
about that, honey.

20:23.290 --> 20:26.670
I've never been anything
but in awe of your brain.

20:26.670 --> 20:28.120
God knows
where you got it,

20:28.120 --> 20:29.960
'cause you didn't get it
from either of your parents.

20:31.790 --> 20:35.500
You know, you really freaked out
Jo with those baby hats.

20:35.500 --> 20:38.080
Well, I didn't mean
to freak her out. I...

20:38.080 --> 20:40.040
Give her
a little nudge, maybe.

20:40.040 --> 20:42.000
[ Chuckles ]

20:42.000 --> 20:43.000
[ Chuckles ]

20:43.000 --> 20:44.540
[ Crunches ]

20:44.540 --> 20:46.380
Woman on P.A.:
Chris Boddam to Admitting.

20:46.380 --> 20:48.040
Chris Boddam to Admitting.

20:48.040 --> 20:49.250
[ Elevator bell dings ]

20:49.250 --> 20:51.170
Mm. Okay. Thanks.

20:51.170 --> 20:53.170
Why do I have a request
for a comment

20:53.170 --> 20:55.330
on the "Maggie Pierce/
Ellis Grey" story?

20:55.330 --> 20:57.500
Oh, my God, Richard.
I'm so sorry.

20:57.500 --> 20:59.620
I was doing that podcast,
and we started talking about

20:59.620 --> 21:01.210
how I got into surgery and
genetics, and then suddenly --

21:01.210 --> 21:03.210
You were telling the entire
medical community

21:03.210 --> 21:05.920
that Ellis and I
had an affair?

21:05.920 --> 21:08.500
Richard, I'm so sorry.

21:08.500 --> 21:09.830
I-I-I didn't think --

21:09.830 --> 21:11.500
No, you didn't.

21:11.500 --> 21:17.290
♪♪

21:23.170 --> 21:25.290
Thank you. All right.
Neurovascular bundle

21:25.290 --> 21:27.790
seems to be intact
and tension-free.

21:27.790 --> 21:29.290
Jo: Blood flow
looks nice.

21:29.290 --> 21:30.670
Link: And I'm liking
the bone alignment.

21:30.670 --> 21:32.330
-Nico, we good?
-Beautiful.

21:32.330 --> 21:34.790
Excellent.
Rounding third.

21:34.790 --> 21:36.000
So, what's up with Karev?

21:36.000 --> 21:37.170
He wants a kid
and you don't?

21:37.170 --> 21:38.670
Well, I thought
I did someday --

21:38.670 --> 21:41.170
until someday started
sounding like today.

21:41.170 --> 21:42.960
Well, I can tell you
that it's not all bad.

21:42.960 --> 21:44.080
I mean,
Harriet right now

21:44.080 --> 21:45.790
is learning how to pronounce
her "K" words,

21:45.790 --> 21:47.500
which sound more like T's.

21:47.500 --> 21:49.120
So she's got a little friend
named Coco --

21:49.120 --> 21:50.540
she calls her Toto.
[ Chuckles ]

21:50.540 --> 21:52.420
And it's got to be
the cutest thing ever.

21:52.420 --> 21:54.500
Right, but does the cute
outweigh the terror?

21:54.500 --> 21:56.790
The what?
You know,
all that potential heartache.

21:56.790 --> 21:59.170
Little humans with giant heads
who are gonna get hurt

21:59.170 --> 22:00.330
and picked on
and have nightmares

22:00.330 --> 22:01.790
and wonder
why they were born.

22:01.790 --> 22:02.830
And even
when they're grown up,

22:02.830 --> 22:03.920
you never stop
worrying about them.

22:03.920 --> 22:05.920
I mean, look at Hunter.

22:05.920 --> 22:08.710
He's a freaking major league
baseball player --
Minor league.

22:08.710 --> 22:11.710
Top of his game, the best genes,
and out of nowhere, cancer.

22:11.710 --> 22:13.790
And now his mom is having
a nervous breakdown,

22:13.790 --> 22:15.170
all because
she made the choice

22:15.170 --> 22:16.880
to ruin her life
with a child.

22:18.040 --> 22:19.460
No offense.

22:19.460 --> 22:21.960
Why would I possibly
be offended?

22:21.960 --> 22:23.790
Irrigation, please.

22:24.790 --> 22:27.080
So, on the days we trade,

22:27.080 --> 22:28.460
one of us will drop him off
at daycare

22:28.460 --> 22:29.830
and the other one
will pick him up?

22:29.830 --> 22:31.960
Yeah.
That makes sense.

22:31.960 --> 22:34.460
Okay. Done.

22:34.460 --> 22:36.540
Huh.

22:36.540 --> 22:38.750
You know this will probably
all go out the window

22:38.750 --> 22:40.420
once Teddy has her baby.

22:40.420 --> 22:41.830
You're not gonna know
your 2s from your 3s.

22:41.830 --> 22:43.420
[ Chuckling ] Well,
Teddy is with Koracick now,

22:43.420 --> 22:46.170
and they're on their babymoon
in Palm Springs.

22:46.170 --> 22:47.830
I still don't know
what that is.

22:47.830 --> 22:49.880
Owen, this is not the time
for Teddy feelings.

22:49.880 --> 22:51.500
W-- It's not a feeling.
It's more of --

22:51.500 --> 22:53.790
Okay, still not
the time for it.
Yeah, okay.

22:53.790 --> 22:56.170
Yeah.
I'm gonna text the lawyer

22:56.170 --> 22:58.960
and let her know
that we made a plan.

23:00.960 --> 23:02.500
[ Cellphone buttons clicking ]

23:04.920 --> 23:06.580
Amelia.
[ Cellphone chimes ]

23:06.580 --> 23:08.080
I don't just want you
in Leo's life.

23:08.080 --> 23:09.880
I want you in mine.

23:09.880 --> 23:11.420
Let's not do this.

23:11.420 --> 23:13.080
I chose you.

23:13.080 --> 23:14.880
I choose you.

23:14.880 --> 23:16.290
That's never changed.

23:16.290 --> 23:18.330
Yeah, it did change.
Everything changed.

23:18.330 --> 23:21.170
Things went bad
when Betty went missing

23:21.170 --> 23:23.080
and we thought that
we'd lost Leo, but...

23:23.080 --> 23:25.790
Amelia, we -- now --
Owen, stop.

23:27.170 --> 23:29.500
It changed with Teddy.
That's when it changed.

23:29.500 --> 23:31.460
And I know that this is messy
and it's painful

23:31.460 --> 23:33.420
and it's not
what you wanted,

23:33.420 --> 23:34.920
and that
is no one's fault.

23:34.920 --> 23:38.380
But breaking up with you was
a moment of clarity for me.

23:38.380 --> 23:40.540
And it hurts,

23:40.540 --> 23:42.540
but it hurts less
than the alternative.

23:45.880 --> 23:47.210
Well, you can
have your clarity,

23:47.210 --> 23:49.210
if that's what you want
to call it.

23:49.210 --> 23:50.670
This is not
no one's fault.

23:52.290 --> 23:53.880
This is your fault.

23:53.880 --> 23:55.500
What?

23:55.500 --> 23:58.040
"The clarity hurts less
than the alternative"?

23:58.040 --> 23:59.420
[ Voice breaking ]
The alternative is loving me.

23:59.420 --> 24:01.000
The alternative is
letting me love you,

24:01.000 --> 24:03.500
but you just can't do it.

24:03.500 --> 24:05.540
You have to just
sabotage it.

24:05.540 --> 24:08.210
I tried to convince myself that
this was all the brain tumor,

24:08.210 --> 24:11.210
but, apparently, there's just
some fundamental part of you

24:11.210 --> 24:12.540
that can't love
or be loved.

24:12.540 --> 24:14.170
♪♪

24:14.170 --> 24:17.380
[ Door opens, closes ]

24:18.670 --> 24:20.710
Did I hear
we've got a plan?

24:20.710 --> 24:25.380
♪♪

24:25.380 --> 24:27.120
-"Heepsters."
-Hipsters, Papa.

24:27.120 --> 24:29.620
It's my new English word.

24:29.620 --> 24:33.080
They're making a statement
that they are unique, yes?

24:33.080 --> 24:35.830
Yeah, by dressing
exactly the same.
[ Chuckles ]

24:35.830 --> 24:37.580
Papa...
[ Speaking Italian ]
Please.

24:37.580 --> 24:40.040
In English.
So I can practice.

24:40.040 --> 24:42.170
Va bene.

24:42.170 --> 24:43.880
Papa, this research
really is incredible.

24:43.880 --> 24:45.670
Yes, it is, my boy.
But we need --

24:45.670 --> 24:48.670
And you --
your life is incredible.

24:48.670 --> 24:49.750
Your city is incredible.

24:49.750 --> 24:51.750
I'm so proud of you.

24:51.750 --> 24:53.960
[ Laughs ]

24:53.960 --> 24:55.170
Thank you.

24:55.170 --> 24:57.750
But...how are you?

24:57.750 --> 24:59.290
Really. Because Carina
seems to think --

24:59.290 --> 25:01.960
Ay, Carina. Ay.

25:01.960 --> 25:03.830
She's like your mother.

25:03.830 --> 25:06.960
She worries.
She controls.

25:06.960 --> 25:09.040
You are like me.

25:09.040 --> 25:11.290
You know a good idea
when you hear one.

25:11.290 --> 25:13.120
Carina worries
for good reason.

25:15.460 --> 25:18.830
It hasn't been easy
between us, I know.

25:18.830 --> 25:20.500
Your mother
come between us --

25:20.500 --> 25:23.880
My mother has
nothing to do with this.
Andrea, let me finish.

25:26.420 --> 25:29.920
You move away from me
with Mama.

25:29.920 --> 25:32.080
Then you stay away
for college.

25:32.080 --> 25:34.880
And now residency.

25:34.880 --> 25:37.420
You are distance.

25:37.420 --> 25:40.750
And I know some part
is my fault.

25:40.750 --> 25:44.000
Let me make good.

25:44.000 --> 25:46.170
Andrea,
you do this with me,

25:46.170 --> 25:48.000
I put you in the map!

25:48.000 --> 25:49.540
On the map.

25:49.540 --> 25:52.750
[ Laughs ]
On the map, yes!

25:52.750 --> 25:56.250
Look at you. You are a man,
all on your own.

25:56.250 --> 25:58.960
A good man, too.
I see that.

25:58.960 --> 26:00.920
And handsome like me.
[ Laughs ]

26:00.920 --> 26:02.710
I see you.

26:02.710 --> 26:05.790
But this woman of yours,
she is beyond you.

26:05.790 --> 26:07.540
Wow. Thank you.

26:07.540 --> 26:10.880
Andrea, even I have
heard of Meredith Grey

26:10.880 --> 26:12.790
all the way back home.

26:12.790 --> 26:14.040
She's more than
a beauty --

26:14.040 --> 26:15.500
she is brilliance.

26:15.500 --> 26:16.830
Yeah, I'm aware.

26:16.830 --> 26:19.290
So, then,

26:19.290 --> 26:21.420
we change the world
together.

26:21.420 --> 26:23.580
We save the babies.

26:23.580 --> 26:26.540
My son,
I owe you this.

26:26.540 --> 26:29.170
Let me put you
on the map.

26:30.080 --> 26:31.210
Huh?

26:31.210 --> 26:32.880
Barista:
What can I get you?

26:32.880 --> 26:34.080
[ Respirator hissing ]

26:34.080 --> 26:37.290
-Mm-hmm.
-Easy. Yeah, easy.

26:37.290 --> 26:39.880
So, it uses the ultrasound
to drive the clot busters

26:39.880 --> 26:41.750
directly into the clot?

26:41.750 --> 26:43.710
Not bad
for a child doctor.

26:43.710 --> 26:44.920
What?

26:44.920 --> 26:46.460
[ Laughs ] Nothing.

26:46.460 --> 26:49.920
Um, less of a chance
of intracranial bleeding.

26:49.920 --> 26:52.750
The TPA will release
over the next 12 hours,

26:52.750 --> 26:54.540
and...boom.

26:54.540 --> 26:57.420
No more creepy-looking
blood clots for you, Frank.

26:57.420 --> 26:58.540
Thank you for saying that,

26:58.540 --> 27:01.500
because I thought
I was the only one.

27:01.500 --> 27:03.790
I almost forgot I was
a doctor there for a minute.

27:03.790 --> 27:05.330
[ Laughing ] Right?

27:05.330 --> 27:08.120
Now we have to
figure out why

27:08.120 --> 27:09.880
he's had
two major blood clots

27:09.880 --> 27:12.290
over the last 24 hours.

27:12.290 --> 27:14.540
Link: All right.
Almost finished up here.

27:14.540 --> 27:17.540
Looking good.
Let's update his mom.

27:17.540 --> 27:18.620
Where are they?

27:20.790 --> 27:22.460
[ Sighs ]
They're closing.

27:24.710 --> 27:26.170
[ Exhales sharply ]

27:26.170 --> 27:27.250
You're mad.

27:28.880 --> 27:30.750
No, I'm not mad.

27:30.750 --> 27:32.210
It's your story,

27:32.210 --> 27:33.960
and you have a right
to tell it.

27:33.960 --> 27:36.790
Okay.
Right words.

27:36.790 --> 27:39.000
Wrong tone.

27:39.000 --> 27:41.500
It is my story, and I do have
a right to tell it.

27:43.290 --> 27:45.790
Catherine has cancer.
She's living with cancer.

27:45.790 --> 27:47.420
Yeah, I know that.

27:47.420 --> 27:49.750
And what I think she maybe
doesn't need added to her plate

27:49.750 --> 27:51.000
at this moment

27:51.000 --> 27:52.500
is the world knowing
that her hus--

27:54.250 --> 27:57.290
That her husband
is an adulterer.

27:57.290 --> 27:58.790
I'm -- I'm confused.

27:58.790 --> 28:00.540
Are you cheating
on Catherine?

28:00.540 --> 28:03.250
Huh? Don't be obtuse.
I am not trying to be.

28:03.250 --> 28:06.290
I had an affair with Ellis,
which you just made public.

28:06.290 --> 28:08.620
And you think that that
somehow reflects on Catherine?

28:08.620 --> 28:11.580
Well, it's not part of my story
I'm particularly proud of.

28:11.580 --> 28:20.330
♪♪

28:20.330 --> 28:21.920
It's the part of your story

28:21.920 --> 28:24.580
that culminated in me,
Richard --

28:24.580 --> 28:26.250
in my existence.

28:26.250 --> 28:33.670
♪♪

28:33.670 --> 28:35.210
[ Speaking Italian ]

28:35.210 --> 28:37.750
[ Speaking Italian ]

28:40.540 --> 28:41.960
Hey.

28:41.960 --> 28:43.290
-Hi.
-[ Sighs ]

28:43.290 --> 28:45.710
Everything okay?

28:45.710 --> 28:47.960
My sister is trying to shut down
my father's research project.

28:49.790 --> 28:51.670
She knows. And she speaks
Italian, so it's okay.

28:51.670 --> 28:53.120
Only a little.

28:53.120 --> 28:55.460
Andrea, we cannot
let him do this.

28:55.460 --> 28:57.380
Wait, you want your father
to do research here?

28:57.380 --> 28:59.670
Yes. I-I think
it's a good idea.

28:59.670 --> 29:02.120
I thought you said he has
an untreated mental illness.

29:02.120 --> 29:04.290
-He does.
-He has episodes, okay?

29:04.290 --> 29:06.080
But it's not like
he's dangerous.

29:06.080 --> 29:07.670
Until he is.

29:07.670 --> 29:08.880
It's complicated.

29:08.880 --> 29:10.830
No, it's not complicated,
Andrea.

29:10.830 --> 29:12.040
He didn't even train
in this field.

29:12.040 --> 29:13.330
Yeah, but you did.

29:13.330 --> 29:14.500
So you know better
than anyone

29:14.500 --> 29:15.880
how important
this research is.

29:15.880 --> 29:17.790
Right, but I also know
better than anyone

29:17.790 --> 29:19.460
just how bad he can get.

29:19.460 --> 29:21.420
Andrea, I spent the last
three months with him.

29:21.420 --> 29:22.670
He's not well.

29:22.670 --> 29:24.170
You didn't
grow up with him,

29:24.170 --> 29:25.420
so when he comes calling,
you go running.

29:25.420 --> 29:26.920
And he knows that.

29:26.920 --> 29:30.420
He knows he can manipulate you,
and you're letting him.

29:30.420 --> 29:31.620
I'm signing on
to participate

29:31.620 --> 29:33.380
in a groundbreaking
medical study

29:33.380 --> 29:36.380
that could change
and save a lot of lives.

29:36.380 --> 29:37.960
Excuse me.

29:37.960 --> 29:41.960
♪♪

29:41.960 --> 29:44.040
What would you do
if you were me?

29:45.460 --> 29:48.710
Talk to the chief?

29:48.710 --> 29:50.120
Hm.

29:50.120 --> 29:51.710
♪♪

29:57.960 --> 30:00.460
Woman on P.A.:
Dr. Harrington to the OR.

30:00.460 --> 30:03.670
Dr. Paige Harrington
to the OR.

30:03.670 --> 30:05.790
Did you know?

30:05.790 --> 30:07.040
I know a lot of things.

30:07.040 --> 30:09.040
You'll have to be
more specific.

30:09.040 --> 30:10.880
About DeLuca's dad
and the mania

30:10.880 --> 30:13.380
and the four patients.

30:13.380 --> 30:14.750
I did.

30:14.750 --> 30:16.120
You could've told me.

30:16.120 --> 30:18.710
I did. I said dig deeper,
read my face.

30:18.710 --> 30:20.460
You could've just told me.

30:20.460 --> 30:22.710
No, I couldn't because
I was confided in

30:22.710 --> 30:25.290
by somebody
I care quite a bit about.

30:25.290 --> 30:28.170
So, no, I couldn't.

30:28.170 --> 30:30.710
I don't want to be the guy who
says no to something amazing

30:30.710 --> 30:33.000
because of
a little mental illness.

30:33.000 --> 30:34.620
I mean, look at my mom.

30:34.620 --> 30:37.330
Have you thought about
the ethical ramifications

30:37.330 --> 30:39.040
if this got into
the wrong hands?

30:39.040 --> 30:40.580
Honestly, if it wasn't
for the guy's history,

30:40.580 --> 30:41.920
I wouldn't even think twice.

30:43.210 --> 30:45.080
Does that mean
you're going to approve it?

30:45.080 --> 30:47.040
Mer, it's a womb
outside the mother.

30:47.040 --> 30:48.330
If he pulls this off,

30:48.330 --> 30:50.120
it's an honest-to-God
medical miracle.

30:53.290 --> 30:55.000
Sorry you had to grow up
like that, man.

30:57.290 --> 30:59.080
You told him?

30:59.080 --> 31:00.250
Carina did.

31:01.790 --> 31:03.580
But I told her to.

31:05.170 --> 31:08.250
Mer, he's my dad.

31:08.250 --> 31:10.000
I'm telling you,
I think he's okay.

31:10.000 --> 31:11.880
I know, but, listen,

31:11.880 --> 31:14.170
I have my own complicated
history with my parents,

31:14.170 --> 31:18.540
and I know that my judgment
was very often clouded.

31:18.540 --> 31:21.540
I need you to try
to trust me on this, okay?

31:21.540 --> 31:26.080
♪♪

31:26.080 --> 31:27.460
[ Elevator bell dings ]

31:27.460 --> 31:29.460
Woman on P.A.:
Dr. Thatcher to ICU.

31:29.460 --> 31:32.000
Dr. Rachel Thatcher to ICU.
Hey.

31:32.000 --> 31:33.460
He's okay.

31:33.460 --> 31:35.420
We're moving him
to an ICU room,

31:35.420 --> 31:37.830
and we were able
to place the catheter

31:37.830 --> 31:39.000
to break up the clot.

31:39.000 --> 31:41.420
Oh, my God, Frank.

31:41.420 --> 31:43.290
We ran some tests,
and we think he has something

31:43.290 --> 31:45.210
called Factor V Leiden.

31:45.210 --> 31:47.420
It's a blood-clotting
disorder

31:47.420 --> 31:50.330
that can lead to
an abnormal amount of clots.

31:50.330 --> 31:52.040
-How did he get that?
-It's genetic.

31:52.040 --> 31:53.750
He's had it
his entire life.

31:53.750 --> 31:56.420
It just didn't cause any issues
until he became so sick.

31:56.420 --> 31:58.750
His cough may have actually
saved his life.

31:58.750 --> 32:00.120
He could've died?

32:00.120 --> 32:01.500
Well, yes.

32:01.500 --> 32:03.500
But we were able
to get to it in time.

32:03.500 --> 32:05.710
And it's genetic?

32:05.710 --> 32:06.830
Dad, what are you --

32:06.830 --> 32:09.460
Okay, you need to test her
right away.

32:09.460 --> 32:11.380
Wait. I thought you said
you and Dad didn't know

32:11.380 --> 32:12.500
which of you was
my biological father?

32:12.500 --> 32:13.880
We don't.

32:13.880 --> 32:15.170
We never wanted to know,

32:15.170 --> 32:17.670
and we always said
that we would only find out

32:17.670 --> 32:19.540
if you wanted to.
Which I don't.

32:19.540 --> 32:21.880
But if it's any chance that
you have this Factor V thing,

32:21.880 --> 32:23.580
we need to find out.

32:23.580 --> 32:28.000
♪♪

32:28.000 --> 32:30.250
[ Indistinct conversations ]

32:33.500 --> 32:35.080
Hey.

32:35.080 --> 32:37.880
I said a crappy thing,
and I'm sorry.

32:37.880 --> 32:40.000
Harriet's incredible,

32:40.000 --> 32:42.790
and I know that not all kids
ruin everyone's lives.

32:42.790 --> 32:45.380
They're sleep-depriving,
sticky little monsters

32:45.380 --> 32:47.290
that demand snacks endlessly

32:47.290 --> 32:48.960
and want you to sing
"Row Row Row Your Boat" to them

32:48.960 --> 32:50.500
50 times a day.
[ Scoffs ]

32:50.500 --> 32:54.170
But they also think everything
you say is hilarious.

32:54.170 --> 32:55.920
And when they lay their head
on your shoulder...

32:55.920 --> 32:57.790
[ Sighs ]

32:57.790 --> 33:00.250
...everything seems right.

33:00.250 --> 33:02.500
Yeah,
kids can ruin your life.

33:02.500 --> 33:06.210
But they also give you
a reason to live when...

33:06.210 --> 33:07.960
when life tries
to ruin you.

33:07.960 --> 33:10.920
♪♪

33:10.920 --> 33:14.250
[ Door opens, closes ]

33:15.580 --> 33:17.380
Now, I don't want
to get panicky phone calls

33:17.380 --> 33:18.790
when this takes time,
okay?

33:18.790 --> 33:19.960
It always does.

33:19.960 --> 33:21.710
It's the nature
of the beast.

33:21.710 --> 33:23.790
But I think you two
are in great shape.
Thank you.

33:25.290 --> 33:29.210
I need to make a change.
I'm sorry. Um.

33:29.210 --> 33:30.460
I don't think I should be
on the paperwork.

33:30.460 --> 33:32.080
Amelia,
what are you doing?

33:35.580 --> 33:39.210
I'll be in his life
because Betty wants me to.

33:39.210 --> 33:42.500
Um, I'll see him as much
as you'll let me.

33:42.500 --> 33:44.750
I can be his friend.
I can help.

33:44.750 --> 33:49.250
I will be Auntie Amelia,

33:49.250 --> 33:50.750
who is fundamentally
incapable of love.

33:50.750 --> 33:53.330
Hey, hey. Come on.

33:53.330 --> 33:55.170
We're over, Owen.

33:55.170 --> 33:57.290
So this is
what's best for him.

33:57.290 --> 33:59.380
You heard her --
one home is ideal.

34:00.960 --> 34:02.040
You don't
have to do this.

34:02.040 --> 34:03.250
♪♪

34:03.250 --> 34:04.750
I have clarity
on this, too, Owen.

34:04.750 --> 34:06.920
Leo is yours.

34:06.920 --> 34:08.500
He's always been yours.

34:11.710 --> 34:13.620
I'm sorry
for wasting your time.

34:13.620 --> 34:20.960
♪♪

34:20.960 --> 34:22.460
[ Door opens, closes ]

34:29.250 --> 34:31.420
Wow.

34:31.420 --> 34:35.290
Okay.
So, that's, uh...

34:35.290 --> 34:38.120
That is
your tumor-free leg.

34:38.120 --> 34:40.120
[ Chuckling ]
Oh, thank God.

34:41.210 --> 34:43.830
You can be honest now.

34:43.830 --> 34:45.210
You really think
I can play again?

34:45.210 --> 34:46.540
Well, I'm not gonna make
any promises,

34:46.540 --> 34:49.170
but I've seen plenty of athletes
return to their sport

34:49.170 --> 34:50.670
after this procedure.

34:50.670 --> 34:53.120
Yep. And when you're able,
we'll start physical therapy

34:53.120 --> 34:55.210
and then fit you
with a prosthetic.

34:55.210 --> 34:56.290
It's gonna be
a lot of work, though.

34:56.290 --> 34:57.500
You're gonna have to
re-train your brain

34:57.500 --> 34:59.420
now that your foot
is your knee.

34:59.420 --> 35:01.620
♪ Always searching
for a place to hide away ♪

35:01.620 --> 35:03.000
Training I can do.

35:03.000 --> 35:04.920
[ Crying ]

35:04.920 --> 35:06.500
Jenny,
this is a good thing.

35:08.000 --> 35:09.580
[ Sniffles ]
I know.

35:09.580 --> 35:11.920
Maybe if I'd had three months
to process all this,

35:11.920 --> 35:14.420
I would be crying
a little less right now.

35:14.420 --> 35:17.250
Or...maybe not.

35:17.250 --> 35:20.500
[ Laughter ]

35:20.500 --> 35:23.080
Yeah.
Maybe not.

35:23.080 --> 35:25.250
♪ Counting my conclusions
and my "You shoulds" ♪

35:25.250 --> 35:26.420
-Hey.
-Mm?

35:26.420 --> 35:30.120
♪ And I don't know
what to say ♪

35:30.120 --> 35:33.290
[ Knocks on door ]

35:33.290 --> 35:35.620
Your head turned out
perfectly fine.

35:35.620 --> 35:37.210
Thank you?

35:37.210 --> 35:38.830
[ Laughs ]
I mean, maybe --

35:38.830 --> 35:40.540
maybe it was too big
for regular hats,

35:40.540 --> 35:42.000
but who cares?

35:42.000 --> 35:44.580
You turned out perfect.

35:44.580 --> 35:46.960
But it's my mom's head
you're worried about, right?

35:46.960 --> 35:49.830
You don't want to pass on
the crazy gene to our kids.

35:49.830 --> 35:52.250
Alex, I love your mom.
I do.

35:52.250 --> 35:55.250
I am not afraid
of your genes.

35:55.250 --> 35:58.170
I'm terrified of mine.

35:58.170 --> 35:59.420
You know, every time
I go to the doctor,

35:59.420 --> 36:02.120
I have to write "unknown"
on my medical history.

36:02.120 --> 36:04.290
On both sides.

36:04.290 --> 36:06.580
And I've learned
to live with that

36:06.580 --> 36:09.040
and define myself
by my own terms.

36:09.040 --> 36:12.460
But when it comes
to our kids,

36:12.460 --> 36:14.120
I don't want to not know.

36:14.120 --> 36:16.290
Okay, so,
we will hire someone

36:16.290 --> 36:17.790
to track down
your family and --

36:17.790 --> 36:21.290
No, no, no. I don't --
I don't want to meet them.

36:21.290 --> 36:24.040
I am going to spit
in a tube.

36:24.040 --> 36:25.880
Cool.
[ Chuckles ]

36:25.880 --> 36:28.170
I'm gonna grow
a baby in a bag.

36:28.170 --> 36:31.120
-Wait. What?
-Yeah. A baby in a bag.

36:31.120 --> 36:32.830
[ Monitor beeps ]
♪ Count your sheep and... ♪

36:32.830 --> 36:34.330
[ Chuckling ] Okay.

36:34.330 --> 36:36.170
♪ ...wake
on a brighter day ♪

36:36.170 --> 36:37.250
[ Knock on door ]

36:37.250 --> 36:38.790
Mr. Nelstadt?

36:38.790 --> 36:40.250
Frank.

36:40.250 --> 36:42.460
We got Ella's
test results back.

36:42.460 --> 36:43.960
♪ I'm running out of ways
to see this place ♪

36:43.960 --> 36:45.040
-Dad.
-Yeah.

36:45.040 --> 36:47.920
-You okay?
-Yeah, I'm okay.

36:47.920 --> 36:52.080
-Are you?
-Yeah, I'm good.

36:52.080 --> 36:53.830
I get to wear
one of these things now.

36:53.830 --> 36:55.250
Oh.

36:55.250 --> 36:57.080
I'm gonna need one
in gold, too.

36:59.330 --> 37:01.290
It never mattered to me
which one of you

37:01.290 --> 37:03.580
was my biological dad,

37:03.580 --> 37:05.580
'cause you're both
my dads.

37:05.580 --> 37:08.460
Period. Okay?

37:08.460 --> 37:11.120
So let's not
flip out about this.

37:11.120 --> 37:13.710
I'm talking to you.

37:13.710 --> 37:16.750
I am not flipping!
[ Chuckles ]

37:16.750 --> 37:18.620
I mean,
he coughed up a lung.

37:18.620 --> 37:21.120
[ Laughs ]
I'm allowed
to have a feeling.

37:21.120 --> 37:22.290
[ Laughs ]

37:22.290 --> 37:24.580
[ Beeping continues ]

37:24.580 --> 37:30.040
♪♪

37:30.040 --> 37:32.170
[ Indistinct conversations ]

37:32.170 --> 37:34.580
Woman on P.A.: Annie Abrumian,
return to the Admin Desk.

37:34.580 --> 37:38.620
Annie Abrumian,
return to the Admin Desk.

37:38.620 --> 37:40.500
[ Sighs ]

37:41.750 --> 37:45.580
I'm ashamed
of what I did back then.

37:45.580 --> 37:48.750
But I'm only grateful
for your existence.

37:48.750 --> 37:50.000
I know.

37:51.670 --> 37:53.960
It's a scandal.

37:53.960 --> 37:55.080
I'm a scandal.

37:55.080 --> 37:58.080
No, I'm a scandal.

37:58.080 --> 37:59.920
You're a miracle.

37:59.920 --> 38:02.750
The best of Ellis,
the very best of me,

38:02.750 --> 38:04.790
and the best of
a mother and father

38:04.790 --> 38:06.330
who raised you
so beautifully.

38:09.790 --> 38:11.460
[ Sighs ]

38:11.460 --> 38:14.420
I am proud to be any part
of you, Maggie Pierce.

38:16.420 --> 38:20.330
And if the press asks,
that'll be my only answer.

38:20.330 --> 38:23.120
♪♪

38:23.120 --> 38:24.330
[ Exhales sharply ]

38:24.330 --> 38:26.040
My dad's gonna listen
to that podcast.

38:26.040 --> 38:29.210
He's gonna be
so proud and excited.

38:29.210 --> 38:30.830
And then he's gonna hear me
giving all the credit

38:30.830 --> 38:32.080
to you and Ellis.

38:33.500 --> 38:36.460
Then he's gonna be even more
heartbroken than you were.

38:36.460 --> 38:42.290
♪♪

38:42.290 --> 38:43.830
[ Horn honks in distance,
insects chirping ]

38:43.830 --> 38:45.670
[ Breathing quickly ]

38:45.670 --> 38:47.000
I-I love you.

38:50.120 --> 38:53.710
And I haven't come out
to my mom because...

38:53.710 --> 38:55.290
she will spin out.

38:55.290 --> 38:57.500
And not because
you're not amazing,

38:57.500 --> 38:59.380
and not because
you're a man.

38:59.380 --> 39:01.960
Asian?
[ Laughing ] No.

39:01.960 --> 39:03.460
No, she will --
she will flip out

39:03.460 --> 39:06.040
because it's what
she does.

39:06.040 --> 39:08.580
She flips out when I try
to purchase a backpack.

39:08.580 --> 39:10.670
Literally, I-I --
when I bought this backpack,

39:10.670 --> 39:12.540
she counted the pockets,

39:12.540 --> 39:14.210
and we had
three conversations

39:14.210 --> 39:17.000
about whether it would
hold everything I needed

39:17.000 --> 39:19.540
and all the ways that it could
accidentally choke me.

39:19.540 --> 39:21.500
[ Chuckles ]

39:21.500 --> 39:24.580
You are my first love.

39:24.580 --> 39:26.790
I know I'm not yours,
and that's okay.

39:26.790 --> 39:29.380
But you are mine.

39:29.380 --> 39:31.790
And I want to lock you in
through my eyes

39:31.790 --> 39:33.790
before I see all the death traps
through hers.

39:33.790 --> 39:36.000
